  <article class="container-prose prose-editorial cs-body" set:html={`<h3><b>Educational Case StBuild-to-sell loan MAP Rule (Reg N) mortgage advertisingudy Disclosure</b></h3><p>This case study is hypothetical and for educational purposes only. Scenarios, borrower profiles, loan terms, interest rates, and outcomes are illustrative examples and do not represent current offers or guaranteed terms.</p><p>For specific details including down payment requirements, closing cost estimates, interest rate details, closing cost breakdowns, payment calculations, cash-to-close estimates, or an official Loan Estimate, it is highly recommended you<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a meeting with one of our licensed mortgage advisors</a>.</p><p><b>Learn more:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/24/">Build-to-sell loan Reg Z advertising requirements (§1026.24)</a> – CFPB official regulation</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-12/chapter-X/part-1026">Build-to-sell loan Reg Z full text and compliance</a> – Electronic Code of Federal Regulations</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/interp-24/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Official build-to-sell loan advertising interpretations (§1026.24)</a> – CFPB interpretations</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/12/part-1014" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Build-to-sell loan MAP Rule (Reg N) mortgage advertising</a> – Mortgage advertising rules</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.nmlsconsumeraccess.org/">NMLS Consumer Access – Verify build-to-sell loan lender licensure</a></li></ul><p>Actual loan terms vary by credit profile, property, occupancy, location, market conditions, and lender guidelines. For current options tailored to you,<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a consultation</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/"> apply online</a>.</p><p>Ready to explore your options?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> with a loan advisor.</p>		
					<h2>How This Build-to-Sell Loan Enabled Successful Spec Home Development Strategy</h2>				
		<p>James P., a 52-year-old real estate developer based in Naples, had successfully completed multiple residential development projects over his 20-year career in construction and real estate. As an experienced developer and Step 7 passive investor transitioning between active development and larger-scale projects, James identified a compelling opportunity in a rapidly growing Naples community where demand for new single-family homes significantly exceeded supply—a market condition that creates ideal opportunities for building wealth through strategic spec home development.</p><p>Young families and relocating professionals were flooding into the area attracted by excellent schools, new commercial development, and expanding employment opportunities, but new construction inventory couldn't keep pace with buyer demand. James saw the perfect conditions for spec home development—building high-quality single-family homes designed to appeal to the target buyer demographic, then selling immediately upon completion for strong profit margins that would fuel his transition into larger-scale development projects and eventually passive income streams.</p><p>He'd secured three adjacent vacant lots in a desirable neighborhood with approved building permits, vetted contractors, and detailed construction plans. Market analysis confirmed strong demand with homes in the area selling quickly at attractive values. However, James needed build-to-sell financing specifically designed for developers constructing homes for immediate resale—not long-term rental or owner-occupancy.</p><p>Traditional construction lenders James approached didn't understand spec home development economics. They wanted to qualify him based on personal income as if he were building a primary residence, ignoring that sale proceeds would pay off the construction loan. Their rigid timelines, high rates, and extensive documentation requirements didn't align with his build-to-sell business model of efficient construction followed by immediate profitable sale. James needed financing that recognized spec home development as a business investment with clear profit expectations based on market demand and projected sale values.</p><p>Facing similar challenges?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> to explore your options.</p><h2><b>The Challenge: Why Traditional Construction Loans Didn't Work for Spec Development</b></h2><p>James approached three traditional construction lenders confident his experience and strong track record would make approval straightforward. He'd successfully completed numerous residential projects over two decades. He had excellent credit, substantial cash reserves, and valuable relationships with reputable contractors, architects, and real estate agents. The vacant lots were purchased and ready for immediate construction start. Building permits were approved. Market analysis confirmed strong buyer demand and attractive sale projections.</p><p>Yet all three traditional lenders presented significant obstacles that fundamentally misunderstood spec home development as a business model.</p><h3><b>How Do Traditional Lenders Qualify Build-to-Sell Loan Applications?</b></h3><p>The first major problem was qualification methodology. Traditional construction lenders wanted to qualify James based on his personal income carrying the construction loan as if he were building a primary residence for his own occupancy. They calculated debt-to-income ratios including the construction loan payment against his personal income, completely ignoring that the homes would sell immediately upon completion with sale proceeds paying off the construction financing. This approach treated spec development like personal homebuilding rather than recognizing it as a business investment with clear exit strategy through sale.</p><p>"I felt like lenders didn't understand how spec development works," James explained. "I wasn't building these homes to live in them or hold them long-term. I was building them to sell immediately upon completion for profit. The construction loan would be outstanding for several months maximum—the construction period—then paid off entirely from sale proceeds. But traditional lenders wanted to qualify me as if I'd be carrying three permanent mortgages on my personal income indefinitely. It made no sense for my business model or my path toward larger development projects."</p><h3><b>What Makes Traditional Construction Financing Expensive for Build-to-Sell Loans?</b></h3><p>The second challenge was rate structure and fees. Construction loans for investment or non-owner-occupied properties carried substantially higher interest rates compared to owner-occupied construction. Additionally, lenders imposed significant origination fees, inspection fees at each draw stage, and administrative fees throughout the construction process. When James calculated total financing costs, the traditional construction loan structure would consume much of his projected profit margin, making the spec development financially unattractive compared to other investment opportunities.</p><p>"The economics didn't work with traditional construction financing," James said. "The rates were substantially higher than what I'd expected. The fees added up to significant costs. When I ran the numbers, my profit margins were compressed to the point where the risk-reward ratio didn't justify the project. I needed financing that recognized my business model and offered rates and terms that made spec development financially viable."</p><h3><b>What Occupancy Requirements Block Build-to-Sell Loan Strategies?</b></h3><p>The third obstacle was occupancy requirements and timeline pressure. Some construction lenders required commitment that the developer would occupy the home as a primary residence for a minimum period after completion, or they imposed rate penalties if the home sold too quickly after construction finished. These requirements completely contradicted James's spec development strategy of immediate sale upon completion. Additionally, traditional lenders imposed rigid construction timelines with penalties for delays, not accounting for the reality that weather, permitting, and subcontractor scheduling issues can extend timelines beyond initial projections.</p><h3><b>Why Is Traditional Construction Documentation Burdensome for Build-to-Sell Loans?</b></h3><p>The documentation requirements also created substantial burden. Traditional lenders wanted extensive personal financial documentation—tax returns, bank statements, asset verification, employment history—treating the transaction like a personal home purchase rather than a business investment. They required detailed budgets with line-item breakdowns and insisted on multiple inspections at each construction phase with administrator review before releasing draw funds. The administrative overhead was substantial for a single project—managing three simultaneous spec homes would become overwhelming.</p><p>"I needed lenders who understood spec development as a business, not homebuilding as a personal project," James explained. "Spec development has different economics, different timelines, different exit strategies. Traditional construction lenders couldn't or wouldn't adapt their programs to recognize those differences. I was stuck with financing designed for homeowners, not developers building wealth through strategic real estate development."</p><h3><b>How Did Timing Pressure Impact James's Build-to-Sell Loan Decision?</b></h3><p>The timing added urgency. James had secured the three lots at favorable terms with sellers motivated to close quickly. Building permits were approved with limited validity periods. His preferred contractor had availability in the current construction season but would be committed to other projects if James delayed. The market opportunity was time-sensitive—buyer demand was strong now, but market conditions could shift. Every month of delay meant lost opportunity and potential changes in market dynamics.</p><p>Experiencing similar frustration with construction financing?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> to discuss alternative solutions.</p><h2><b>The Discovery: How James Found Build-to-Sell Financing</b></h2><p>While discussing his financing challenges with a commercial real estate colleague who specialized in development projects, James learned about build-to-sell loan programs designed specifically for spec home developers. His colleague had successfully used build-to-sell financing for multiple projects and enthusiastically explained how these programs work fundamentally differently than traditional construction loans.</p><h3><b>How Are Build-to-Sell Loans Different from Traditional Construction Financing?</b></h3><p>Intrigued but skeptical after three rejections, James scheduled a consultation with a lender specializing in build-to-sell financing for experienced developers. He honestly expected another explanation of why his project "didn't qualify" or another set of requirements he couldn't meet.</p><p>Instead, the conversation revealed a financing approach specifically designed for his business model.</p><p>The build-to-sell loan specialist explained how these programs differ from traditional construction loans. First, they're structured specifically for developers building homes for immediate resale, not owner-occupancy or long-term rental. Second, they qualify borrowers based on project economics—market analysis showing buyer demand, projected sale values, developer experience, and profit margins—rather than personal debt-to-income ratios treating the construction loan as permanent debt. Third, they feature competitive rates reflecting the lower-risk profile of experienced developers with proven track records and clear exit strategies through sale.</p><h3><b>What Made Build-to-Sell Loan Financing Align with James's Strategy?</b></h3><p>"That conversation completely changed my perspective on financing the spec development," James said. "The lender actually understood what I was trying to accomplish—build quality homes, sell them immediately to eager buyers, generate profit, and move to the next project. The qualification focused on what mattered: my development experience, market demand for the homes, projected sale values, and my contractor relationships. It wasn't about whether my personal income could carry three permanent mortgages—it was about whether the project made business sense based on market conditions."</p><h3><b>How Does Developer Experience Impact Build-to-Sell Loan Approval?</b></h3><p>The lender also explained that build-to-sell financing works particularly well for experienced developers with proven track records completing projects on time and within budget. James's 20-year career completing multiple successful developments strengthened his application significantly. His established relationships with licensed contractors, architects, and real estate agents demonstrated professional capability. His market analysis showing strong buyer demand and attractive projected sale values confirmed the business opportunity.</p><h3><b>What Exit Strategy Do Build-to-Sell Loans Require?</b></h3><p>James learned that the loan structure typically involves construction phase financing with flexible draw schedules aligned with completion milestones, competitive rates reflecting spec development rather than permanent financing, and clear expectations for sale and payoff within specified timeframes after construction completion. No personal occupancy requirements. No penalties for quick sales. No treating the financing as if it were permanent debt rather than short-term construction capital.</p><p>"The build-to-sell approach recognized the reality of how spec development works," James added. "Developers don't build homes to live in them—we build homes to sell them profitably. The financing was structured accordingly. It made perfect sense and aligned with my vision of building successful projects that generate capital for larger developments down the road."</p><h2><b>The Solution: Build-to-Sell Loan Approval Process</b></h2><p>James worked with his build-to-sell loan specialist to structure financing for his three-home spec development project. The process focused on his development experience, market analysis demonstrating demand, and project economics rather than treating the transaction like personal homebuilding.</p><h3><b>What Documentation Was Required for Build-to-Sell Loan Approval?</b></h3><p><b>Documentation provided:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Comprehensive market analysis showing strong buyer demand and recent comparable sales</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Detailed construction plans and specifications designed for target buyer demographic</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Licensed contractor credentials with references from previous successful projects</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Projected construction timeline with specific completion milestones</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Projected sale values based on comparable properties and current market conditions</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">James's 20-year development track record with completed project portfolio</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Excellent credit score with strong payment history</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Appropriate down payment and construction reserves</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Vacant lot purchase documentation with clear title</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Building permits approved and ready for construction start</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Established relationships with real estate agents for marketing and sale</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Insurance and liability coverage for construction period</li></ul><h3><b>How Long Does Build-to-Sell Loan Approval Take?</b></h3><p><b>The approval process:</b></p><ol><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Initial consultation (Week 1)</b> — Discussed spec development strategy and financing structure</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Document submission (Weeks 1-2)</b> — Provided market analysis, construction plans, developer portfolio</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Market analysis review (Week 2)</b> — Lender evaluated buyer demand and sale projections</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Developer experience verification (Week 3)</b> — Reviewed James's completed project track record</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Contractor evaluation (Week 3)</b> — Assessed builder credentials and reliability</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Build-to-sell loan approval (Week 4)</b> — Approved for construction financing for three spec homes</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Construction start (Week 5)</b> — Builder began foundation work on first property</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Staggered construction schedule</b> — Started second and third homes at intervals</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Draw schedule established</b> — Periodic draws based on completion milestones</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Construction progress (Months 2-6)</b> — Regular inspections and draw releases</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>First home completion (Month 6)</b> — Certificate of occupancy and immediate listing</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Pre-sale activity (Month 5-6)</b> — Real estate agent marketing to prospective buyers</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>First sale (Month 7)</b> — Sold first completed spec home, paid off portion of construction financing</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Second and third home completions (Months 7-8)</b> — Additional homes completed</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>All sales completed (Month 9)</b> — Entire project sold, build-to-sell loan fully paid off</li></ol><p>The build-to-sell lender evaluated James's development experience, analyzed market demand and projected sale values, and approved financing based on spec home development economics rather than treating the project like owner-occupied construction.</p><p>"The build-to-sell loan process recognized my business model from day one," James explained. "They understood I was building to sell, not to live in or hold long-term. The qualification focused on market demand, my track record, and project viability. Within weeks I was approved and breaking ground on homes that would generate strong profits and fuel my next development phase."</p><p>Ready to purchase?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/purchase-inquiry/"> Submit a purchase inquiry</a> to discuss your build-to-sell scenario.</p><h2><b>The Results: James Completes Build-to-Sell Project Successfully</b></h2><p>James successfully completed construction on all three spec homes over approximately eight months. The properties sold quickly to eager buyers at strong sale values, generating attractive profit margins. The build-to-sell financing was paid off at each sale closing, and the project validated James's strategic approach to spec home development.</p><h3><b>What Results Did James Achieve with Build-to-Sell Loan Financing?</b></h3><p><b>Final build-to-sell outcome:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Three single-family spec homes completed on schedule</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">High-quality construction appealing to target buyer demographic</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Modern finishes and energy-efficient systems</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Open floor plans and desirable features</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">All properties sold quickly after completion</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Strong sale values meeting or exceeding projections</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Attractive profit margins on each home</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Competitive interest rate structure for construction financing</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Flexible draw schedule aligned with milestones</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Minimal administrative burden enabling efficient management</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Zero occupancy requirement—immediate sale after completion</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Construction timeline: Approximately eight months from start to final sale</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Properties: 3BR/2BA and 4BR/2.5BA spec homes, Naples desirable neighborhood</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Business goal: ACHIEVED ✓</li></ul><h3><b>How Did Build-to-Sell Loan Compare to Traditional Construction Financing?</b></h3><p><b>Traditional construction financing vs. build-to-sell loan qualification:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Traditional approach:</b> Required personal debt-to-income qualification, treated like permanent financing</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Build-to-sell approach:</b> Qualified based on project economics and developer experience</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Rate structure:</b> Competitive rates for experienced developers with proven track records</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Occupancy requirements:</b> No personal occupancy needed—immediate sale permitted</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Administrative burden:</b> Streamlined processes enabling efficient project management</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Business model alignment:</b> Perfect fit for spec development exit strategy</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Project success:</b> All three homes sold profitably</li></ul><p>James's spec home development generated strong profits that validated his business model and provided capital for his next development phase. The project demonstrated the viability of build-to-sell financing for experienced developers working in high-demand markets with limited new construction inventory.</p><h3><b>What Are James's Long-Term Plans After Build-to-Sell Loan Success?</b></h3><p>"The build-to-sell financing gave me exactly what I needed—competitive rates, reasonable terms, and lenders who understood my business model," James explained. "I built quality homes buyers wanted, sold them quickly in a strong market, and generated profits that will fund my next projects. The economics worked perfectly because the financing was designed for spec development, not homeowners."</p><p>James views this project as validation of his spec home development strategy and the beginning of his transition toward larger-scale projects. The profits from these three homes provided capital for acquiring additional land, establishing stronger contractor relationships, and expanding his development operations. He's already identified the next opportunity—a larger subdivision with multiple lots where he can apply the same build-to-sell strategy at greater scale.</p><h3><b>How Will James Continue Building Wealth Through Development?</b></h3><p>"This isn't just about three spec homes—it's about building a development business that generates consistent profits and eventually transitions into larger passive income opportunities," James added. "By completing successful projects, I'm establishing relationships, proving my capabilities, and building capital for bigger developments. Each project is a stepping stone toward larger opportunities and eventually the financial freedom that comes from successful real estate development."</p><p>When he's ready for the next build-to-sell project, James knows the financing structure works efficiently for his business model. He's established relationships with lenders, contractors, and real estate agents who understand spec home development. The strategy is proven. The economics are validated. The scaling path toward larger projects and passive income is clear.</p><p>If James expands into build-to-rent projects alongside his spec home development, he may use equity from existing properties through<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/heloc/"> HELOC</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/home-equity-loan/"> Home Equity Loan</a> products to fund down payments on new construction while diversifying his development portfolio.</p><p>Ready to get started?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/"> Get approved</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a call</a> to discuss your strategy.</p><h2><b>Exploring Other Construction Loan Options?</b></h2><p>While James used build-to-sell financing for spec home development, construction financing works for multiple scenarios:</p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Building for rental income? See how<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/build-to-rent-loan"> investors use build-to-rent for rental property construction</a></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Building primary residence? See how<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/construction-loan/"> families use construction-to-permanent loans for custom homes</a></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/">View all case studies</a> to find success stories matching your situation</li></ul><h2><b>Key Takeaways for Real Estate Developers Considering Build-to-Sell Loans</b></h2><h3><b>What Can Developers Learn from This Build-to-Sell Loan Success?</b></h3><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Build-to-sell financing qualifies based on project economics and developer experience, not personal debt-to-income ratios</b>—enabling developers to scale multiple projects simultaneously (<a href="https://www.hud.gov/">HUD construction guidelines</a>)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Experienced developers with proven track records unlock competitive rates</b>—James's 20-year history completing successful projects strengthened his build-to-sell loan qualification and improved financing terms</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Market analysis demonstrating buyer demand validates spec development business model</b>—comprehensive comparable sales research and demand analysis support loan approval</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Quality contractor relationships and reliable construction timelines reduce lender risk</b>—established partnerships with licensed contractors improve build-to-sell loan approval odds</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Clear exit strategy through immediate sale aligns with build-to-sell loan structure</b>—financing designed for quick completion and sale, not long-term holding</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Spec development in high-demand markets with limited inventory creates compelling profit opportunities</b>—building where demand exceeds supply validates business case</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Think strategically about development as wealth-building</b>—successful developers view each build-to-sell project as one step in a larger strategy. James's goal isn't just three spec homes; it's building a development business that generates consistent profits, establishes credibility, and eventually transitions into larger projects and passive income streams that create financial freedom and generational wealth</li></ul><p>Have questions about build-to-sell financing?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> with a loan advisor experienced in development projects.</p><h2><b>Alternative Loan Programs for Developers</b></h2><p>If build-to-sell financing isn't the perfect fit, consider these alternatives:</p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/build-to-rent-loans">Build-to-Rent Loan</a> – Construction financing for rental property development</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/fix-and-flip-loan/">Fix and Flip Loan</a> – Short-term financing for renovation and resale projects</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/hard-money-loan/">Hard Money Loan</a> – Fast acquisition financing for development opportunities</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/construction-loan/">Construction Loan</a> – Build custom primary residence with construction-to-permanent financing</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/portfolio-loan/">Portfolio Loan</a> – Finance multiple properties with flexible terms</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/dscr-loan/">DSCR Loan</a> – Purchase completed investment properties based on cash flow</li></ul><p><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/">Explore all loan programs</a> to find your best option.</p><h2><b>Helpful Build-to-Sell Loan Resources</b></h2><p><b>Learn more about this loan program:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/build-to-sell-loans">Complete Build-to-Sell Guide</a> - Detailed requirements and qualification guidelines</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/build-to-sell-calculator">Build-to-Sell Calculator</a> - Estimate project costs and profit projections</li></ul><p><b>Similar success stories:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/build-to-rent-loan">How an investor used build-to-rent for rental property construction</a> - New construction for rentals</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/construction-loan/">Family's construction-to-permanent loan success</a> - Building custom primary residence</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/">View all case studies</a> - Browse by development strategy</li></ul><p><b>External authoritative resources:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.hud.gov/">HUD construction guidelines</a> - Federal housing administration construction standards</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.nahb.org/">NAHB builder resources</a> - National Association of Home Builders industry data</li></ul><p><b>Ready to get started?</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/">Apply online</a> - Start your application today</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/">Schedule a consultation</a> - Discuss your spec development strategy</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/discovery-quiz/">Take the discovery quiz</a> - Clarify your development goals</li></ul><p>Need local expertise?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/get-a-local-introduction/"> Get introduced to trusted partners</a> including contractors, architects, and real estate agents specializing in new construction.</p><p><b>Disclosure:</b> NEXA Mortgage, LLC dba Stairway Mortgage — NMLS #1660690 • Equal 